snippet.textDisplay: Alec Stewart and Nasser Hussain usually talk sense but after Day 1 they spoke utter drivel by running through the scorecard and saying that a number of England batsman got themselves in and then erred. Nearly all the batsmen repeatedly rode their luck and could easily have been out several times (so to speak) before ultimately falling. Poor had enough luck to last an entire career; Root could have been out on at least three occasions before his demise. At least 100 of the runs were streaks associated with occasions when England got away with close chances for South Africa. On another day England could credibly have been out for around 150. I'm English but we must try to be objective on our assessments; none of out batsmen was 'in and set' on Day 1. I still firmly believe that England have a far better depth of players than South Africa notwithstanding injuries. The South Africa top three are weak, although Elgar is probably the most competent of those. Patently silly how many no balls each side has bowled by mid Day 2 that haven't been called; they only seem to scrutinise these when a wicket has ostensibly fallen but they should be monitoring them throughout the match.

snippet.textDisplay:
Apart from Ben Stokes, can anyone name any England test players, who's batting has actually improved since their debut?

Root's getting worse by the week .... Bairstow's form has dropped off a cliff .... Butler looks like a frozen rabbit .... Broad looks like a rampant rabbit vibrator .... Woakes looked like an allrounder when he first started but has gone downhill .... Anderson used to be able to stay around for an hour or two .... Curran used to look promising.

They'll probably ruin Pope and they've tried their best to sabotage Burns.

There's no point even finding decent batsman because they'll just get steadily worse after a few years in this England team!
